1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,620
Welcome to this new deep dive.

2
00:00:02,620 --> 00:00:08,140
Today we ask ourselves a seemingly simple question, but one that actually shakes the foundations of our

3
00:00:08,140 --> 00:00:09,140
society.

4
00:00:09,140 --> 00:00:14,640
Does school create citizens? We will explore a topic we take almost for granted, starting

5
00:00:14,640 --> 00:00:19,580
from a truly revolutionary economic study, signed by researchers Alesina, Giuliano,

6
00:00:19,580 --> 00:00:20,580
and Reich.

7
00:00:20,580 --> 00:00:24,780
You know, we often like to imagine that public school was born from a pure, noble

8
00:00:24,780 --> 00:00:26,940
impulse of philanthropy toward the masses.

9
00:00:26,940 --> 00:00:32,340
Well, the data tells us of a much, much more counterintuitive, and frankly

10
00:00:32,340 --> 00:00:33,340
fascinating genesis.

11
00:00:33,340 --> 00:00:35,539
Let's get straight to the heart of it.

12
00:00:35,539 --> 00:00:40,740
Think of this very famous quote by Massimo d'Azeglio; it perfectly illustrates what

13
00:00:40,740 --> 00:00:43,859
the mentality of the 19th-century elites was.

14
00:00:43,859 --> 00:00:49,100
At the time, the masses were absolutely not seen as active citizens with rights;

15
00:00:49,100 --> 00:00:53,659
no, they were considered more like a sort of clay, a raw material that desperately

16
00:00:53,660 --> 00:00:55,820
needed to be molded.

17
00:00:55,820 --> 00:01:00,900
School, from this perspective, was the great cauldron in which to melt disparate identities, languages, and cultures

18
00:01:00,900 --> 00:01:04,340
to literally forge a united people.

19
00:01:04,340 --> 00:01:08,579
It is a concept that radically changes our perspective on the entire system.

20
00:01:08,579 --> 00:01:13,620
Here is how we will move today: first we will explore the secret origin of school, then

21
00:01:13,620 --> 00:01:19,219
we will talk about dictatorships and democracies, moving on to the so-called threat of democracy.

22
00:01:19,219 --> 00:01:25,099
We will look at the historical evidence and finally analyze the very interesting strategy of the colonizers.

23
00:01:25,099 --> 00:01:26,539
It will be quite a journey.

24
00:01:26,539 --> 00:01:31,659
Let's start with the first point on our list: the secret origin of school.

25
00:01:31,659 --> 00:01:33,819
We need to debunk a myth right away.

26
00:01:33,819 --> 00:01:37,299
Mass schooling was not born out of pure altruism.

27
00:01:37,299 --> 00:01:40,379
The real motivations were coldly strategic.

28
00:01:40,379 --> 00:01:45,060
It is all summed up in the concept of Nation Building, the construction of the nation.

29
00:01:45,060 --> 00:01:50,379
Mind you, we are not talking about State Building, that is, building public offices or collecting

30
00:01:50,379 --> 00:01:51,379
taxes.

31
00:01:51,379 --> 00:01:55,780
Nation Building is a calculated process; it is the art of making people feel part

32
00:01:55,780 --> 00:02:00,100
of a single large group, so that they feel they have something in common and do not want, for

33
00:02:00,100 --> 00:02:01,579
example, to divide the country.

34
00:02:01,579 --> 00:02:06,140
And guess what, school classrooms were the perfect tool to do it.

35
00:02:06,140 --> 00:02:10,780
This thought by Napoleon in 1805 hits the nail right on the head.

36
00:02:10,780 --> 00:02:14,699
As early as the beginning of the 1800s, political leaders had understood everything.

37
00:02:14,699 --> 00:02:18,460
Elementary schools were formidable ideological tools.

38
00:02:18,460 --> 00:02:22,539
Teaching loyalty to the system from the moment children could barely walk

39
00:02:22,539 --> 00:02:27,460
was, quite simply, the cheapest and most effective way to prevent disorder and stabilize

40
00:02:27,460 --> 00:02:29,379
regimes in the long term.

41
00:02:29,379 --> 00:02:31,099
Let's move on to the second chapter.

42
00:02:31,099 --> 00:02:34,340
Dictatorships, democracies, and nations.

43
00:02:34,340 --> 00:02:39,340
The study we are analyzing uses a brilliant economic model to explain all this.

44
00:02:39,340 --> 00:02:42,379
It is based on the so-called theory of distance.

45
00:02:42,379 --> 00:02:46,620
Simply put, imagine that every citizen has their own political ideas.

46
00:02:46,620 --> 00:02:51,699
If the government's choices are too far from those ideals, the citizen suffers, feeling

47
00:02:51,699 --> 00:02:53,819
a cost, a dissatisfaction.

48
00:02:53,819 --> 00:02:59,099
If this discontent grows too much, some regions might even want to secede.

49
00:02:59,099 --> 00:03:04,500
Education acts chemically to reduce this distance, homogenizing minds and keeping them

50
00:03:04,500 --> 00:03:06,580
close to the center of government.

51
00:03:06,580 --> 00:03:10,780
And here, a fantastic paradox emerges between two types of dictatorships.

52
00:03:10,780 --> 00:03:15,820
A completely secure dictator who does not fear revolts has absolutely no desire to

53
00:03:15,820 --> 00:03:19,980
spend money on schools; extracting wealth is enough for him, and that's it.

54
00:03:19,980 --> 00:03:25,780
But an elite or a threatened dictator who feels the breath of the population on their neck

55
00:03:25,780 --> 00:03:31,380
changes tactics, opens their wallet, and invests heavily in education, because in order

56
00:03:31,379 --> 00:03:36,379
to indoctrinate the masses, convince them to appreciate the regime, and basically save

57
00:03:36,379 --> 00:03:37,379
their own seat.

58
00:03:37,379 --> 00:03:42,219
And this brings us to chapter 3, the threat of democracy.

59
00:03:42,219 --> 00:03:47,379
Hold on tight, because the historical data here shows a truly ruthless truth.

60
00:03:47,379 --> 00:03:52,219
The imminent arrival of the right to vote literally terrified rulers.

61
00:04:01,379 --> 00:04:05,900
Compulsory education did not arrive hand in hand with modern democracies.

62
00:03:56,379 --> 00:03:59,379
No, it preceded them by an average of a whopping 50 years.

63
00:03:59,379 --> 00:04:01,379
The elites reasoned like this.

64
00:04:01,379 --> 00:04:05,900
Before these masses get the right to vote, we must make sure we have taught

65
00:04:05,900 --> 00:04:08,979
them how to vote while keeping our values intact.

66
00:04:08,979 --> 00:04:12,699
It's a literal three-step defense mechanism.

67
00:04:12,699 --> 00:04:16,019
First, there is a major risk of revolutions on the horizon.

68
00:04:16,019 --> 00:04:21,180
Second, the elites scramble for cover by imposing mass education across the country.

69
00:04:21,180 --> 00:04:27,339
Third, the new, now culturally homogenized and aligned population stops wanting to cut off

70
00:04:27,340 --> 00:04:32,700
heads, the revolution deflates, the country's unity is saved, and the rich stay rich,

71
00:04:32,700 --> 00:04:35,780
school as the ultimate social shock absorber.

72
00:04:35,780 --> 00:04:40,620
Let's look at the proof of facts, chapter 4, the proof of history.

73
00:04:40,620 --> 00:04:43,820
This is not just theory drawn on a blackboard.

74
00:04:43,820 --> 00:04:49,500
History proves it to us, step by step, look at this impressive timeline,

75
00:04:49,500 --> 00:04:54,260
in Prussia, in France, in Victorian England, and even in Japan.

76
00:04:54,259 --> 00:04:59,659
Every time there were peasant revolts, revolutions, or pressures to expand suffrage,

77
00:04:59,659 --> 00:05:02,060
what was the state's very first response?

78
00:05:02,060 --> 00:05:05,539
Major school reforms: they built classrooms.

79
00:05:05,539 --> 00:05:11,060
The pattern repeats itself identically, across completely different continents and cultures, but to play

80
00:05:11,060 --> 00:05:15,779
devil's advocate, what if school had been just a generous concession

81
00:05:15,779 --> 00:05:18,379
to satisfy the people who demanded it?

82
00:05:18,379 --> 00:05:23,540
Well, if that were the case, welfare reforms, such as healthcare or unemployment benefits,

83
00:05:23,540 --> 00:05:28,540
would have arrived at the same time, but that's not how it went.

84
00:05:28,540 --> 00:05:33,560
Welfare arrived much, much later, almost always only after the people had

85
00:05:33,560 --> 00:05:35,060
actually gained the vote.

86
00:05:35,060 --> 00:05:41,259
In short, the poor demanded bread and wages, but the elites provided schools to guarantee order.

87
00:05:41,259 --> 00:05:46,500
And mind you, we are not talking about a dynamic limited to the dust of the 1800s.

88
00:05:46,740 --> 00:05:51,939
The researchers of the study went much further, analyzing a gigantic sample.

89
00:05:51,939 --> 00:05:59,459
We are talking about data from a whopping 172 countries collected from 1925 to 2014.

90
00:05:59,459 --> 00:06:01,939
And what do these modern numbers tell us?

91
00:06:01,939 --> 00:06:03,819
They remove all doubt.

92
00:06:03,819 --> 00:06:08,500
If we look at today's non-democratic regimes, when they are under a serious threat,

93
00:06:08,500 --> 00:06:13,379
such as major government crises or attempted revolutions, an anomalous spike occurs

94
00:06:13,379 --> 00:06:15,540
in primary school enrollment.

95
00:06:15,660 --> 00:06:19,460
We are talking about increases of over 20% in the following decade.

96
00:06:19,460 --> 00:06:21,220
The golden rule stands.

97
00:06:21,220 --> 00:06:25,220
When the throne creaks, the education machine accelerates to the maximum.

98
00:06:25,220 --> 00:06:31,100
And here we are at chapter 5, the last one: the strategy of the colonizers.

99
00:06:31,100 --> 00:06:34,020
This is perhaps the most revealing passage.

100
00:06:34,020 --> 00:06:38,060
The exception that proves the rule in an almost dramatic way.

101
00:06:38,060 --> 00:06:43,140
We have seen that local elites built schools to create an identity and avoid being

102
00:06:43,139 --> 00:06:45,740
overthrown, but the colonial empires?

103
00:06:45,740 --> 00:06:50,139
They could always get on their ships and return to their homeland; they had no

104
00:06:50,139 --> 00:06:54,300
incentive to create a strong national identity in the occupied country.

105
00:06:54,300 --> 00:06:59,860
In fact, their logic was divide and conquer; they deliberately kept the population

106
00:06:59,860 --> 00:07:05,219
fragmented, divided, to prevent them from presenting a united front in a collective rebellion.

107
00:07:05,219 --> 00:07:09,459
We find this highly cynical approach everywhere.

108
00:07:09,540 --> 00:07:14,180
In the British Caribbean, compulsory school was simply ignored for decades.

109
00:07:14,180 --> 00:07:18,540
In Kenya, British officials tried in every way to obstruct a bridge language

110
00:07:18,540 --> 00:07:21,860
like Swahili, out of fear that it might unite the various tribes.

111
00:07:21,860 --> 00:07:26,500
And in Ethiopia, the Italian colonial authorities pushed for teaching almost exclusively

112
00:07:26,500 --> 00:07:31,100
in local dialects, with the precise and declared intent of sowing disunity among the Ethiopian

113
00:07:31,100 --> 00:07:32,100
peoples.

114
00:07:32,100 --> 00:07:35,420
And so we come to the conclusion of our journey.

115
00:07:35,420 --> 00:07:40,660
When we look at raw data and history with a capital H, the super-romantic image

116
00:07:40,660 --> 00:07:43,900
of public education that we have in our heads fades a bit.

117
00:07:43,900 --> 00:07:48,700
The entire modern school system has been shaped globally by the naked

118
00:07:48,700 --> 00:07:51,420
and raw need of elites to survive.

119
00:07:51,420 --> 00:07:56,700
Mass education was not designed to liberate, but to peacefully absorb

120
00:07:56,700 --> 00:08:01,379
and control the enormous challenges that would come with universal suffrage.

121
00:08:01,379 --> 00:08:07,500
And in light of all this, the research leaves us with a very, very powerful question.

122
00:08:07,500 --> 00:08:12,339
Let's look at how we frame and evaluate education today, from kindergarten all the way

123
00:08:12,339 --> 00:08:13,500
to the end of high school.

124
00:08:13,500 --> 00:08:18,019
How much of that ancient design of social control still lives today at our school

125
00:08:18,019 --> 00:08:19,019
desks?

126
00:08:19,019 --> 00:08:22,779
Are we truly forming critical thinkers, or just obedient citizens?

127
00:08:22,779 --> 00:08:26,939
It's a fascinating key to reinterpreting the institutions that surround us.

128
00:08:26,939 --> 00:08:30,500
We'll stop here, but you keep thinking about it.

129
00:08:30,500 --> 00:08:34,779
Thank you for following this deep dive into numbers and history. Until next time.